:"1374–Overleden","1376–Female":"1376–Overleden","Abt 1395":"circa 1395","1500":"1500","1376":"1376","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","England, United Kingdom":"England"},"en":{"Abt 1395–1417":"about 1395–1417","1395–1417":"1395–1417","1395–1418":"1395–1418","1418–1500":"1418–1500","1374–Male":"1374–Deceased","1376–Female":"1376–Deceased","Abt 1395":"about 1395","1500":"1500","1376":"1376","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","England, United Kingdom":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Higins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hUiginn</b> ‘descendant of <i>Uiginn</i>’, a byname meaning ‘viking, sea-rover’ (from Old Norse <i>víkingr</i>). Compare   McGuigan  .","English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of <b>Higgin</b>, itself either a Lancashire variant of <b>Huggin</b> (from a pet form of   Hugh  ), or a variant of   Hickin   (from a pet form of   Richard  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. See   Hick   and compare   Higson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Higgens","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Higgins  ."]},{"name":"McGuigan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam, Mairead.","Irish (northern): perhaps an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mag Uiginn</b> ‘son of the viking’ (see   Higgins   1).","Irish (northern): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Guagáin</b>, a shortened form of <b>Mag Eochagáin</b>, son of <i>Eochagán</i>, a diminutive of <i>Eochaidh</i> ‘horseman’. Compare   Geoghegan  ."]},{"name":"Haggins","meanings":["Scottish variant of Irish   Higgins  ."]},{"name":"Heggins","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Higgins   1."]},{"name":"Kiggins","meanings":["Irish (Galway and Mayo) and Manx: shortened Anglicized form (with English excrescent <i>-s</i>) of Gaelic <b>Mag Uiginn</b> ‘son of the Viking’ (see   Higgins  )."]}]},{"name":"Hugh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Hugues</i>, <i>Hugo</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’. It was originally a short form of various compound names containing this element. This was borne by the aristocracy of medieval France, adopted by the Normans, and introduced by them to Britain. It was consistently one of the most popular boys' names in the Middle Ages in England, but fell out of favour in the 16th century until it was revived in the 20th century. Little Hugh of Lincoln was a child supposed in the Middle Ages to have been murdered by Jews in about  1255 , a legend responsible for several outbursts of anti-Semitism at various times. The story is referred to by  Chaucer  in The Prioress's Tale. He is not to be confused with  St Hugh of Lincoln  (  1140–1200 ), bishop of Lincoln (  1186–1200 ), who was noted for his charity and good works, his piety, and his defence of the Church against the State. Since the later Middle Ages <i>Hugh</i> has also been used as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic name Aodh ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Hugh Higins was born about 1395, his father, Hugh Higins Ist, was 22 and his mother, Mrs. Hugh Higgins 1st, was 20. He had at least 1 daughter with Henrietta Brenton. He died in 1417, in England, at the age of 23."},"et":{"Abt 1395–1417":"umbes 1395–1417","1395–1417":"1395–1417","1395–1418":"1395–1418","1418–1500":"1418–1500","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1376–Female":"1376–Surnud","Abt 1395":"umbes 1395","1500":"1500","1376":"1376","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","1418":"1418","1417":"1417","England, United Kingdom":"England"},"fi":{"Abt 1395–1417":"noin 1395–1417","1395–1417":"1395–1417","1395–1418":"1395–1418","1418–1500":"1418–1500","1374–Male":"1374–Kuollut","1376–Female":"1376–Kuollut","Abt 1395":"noin 1395","1500":"1500","1376":"1376","1374":"1374","1395":"1395","1418":"1418","1417":"1417",